directions.Direction: Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
Bring a pot of salted water to a boil. Cook pasta 1-2 minutes less than al dente. Strain and rinse with cool water to prevent from cooking further.
While waiting for the pasta to boil, add butter to a large sauce pot over medium heat.
Once melted and hot, add in the onion. Season with salt and pepper and saut√© until translucent.
Whisk in the flour and cook until the flour smell disappears (about 2-3 minutes).
Slowly pour in the milk and heavy cream, constantly whisking.
Mix in garlic powder and mustard.
Bring to a light simmer and cook until the sauce thickens slightly.
Once the sauce is think, turn the heat off and add in the american cheese.
Once the american cheese has melted, add in 12 oz of cheddar cheese and mix until combined.
Taste and season with salt and pepper (we like a lot of pepper and a little bit of salt as the cheese is already salty).
Now mix in the noodles until evening coated with the cheese sauce.
Mix olive oil and breadcrumbs in a small bowl.
Pour into a baking dish, top with remaining cheddar cheese, and breadcrumbs.
Bake for 15-20 minutes or until the breadcrumbs are golden brown.
Enjoy!
Cook bacon until crispy. Remove form pan and chop into small pieces once cooled. Save 1 tbsp of bacon grease.
Bring a pot of water to a boil and add in green beans. Blanch for 5 minutes, drain, and dump into an ice bath. Strain again and set aside.
Preheat oven to 350 degrees.

Melt bacon grease and butter in a large pot on medium heat. Once melted, whisk in flour. Cook until flour smell disappears (about 1 minute). Whisk in heavy cream and stir until slightly thickened. Turn heat to low and add in boursin, cheddar cheese, cream of mushroom soup, spices, soy sauce, and worcestershire sauce.
Turn off heat and add in green beans, bacon, and 1/2 c of fried onions.

Pour green bean mixture into a greased baking dish and top with at least 1 c of fried onions. Bake for 45 minutes or until casserole is heated all the way through and bubbling (if the onions start to get dark, top the casserole with aluminum foil).
Enjoy!

ingredients.Name: chicken broth (omit if using to stuff inside turkey)

directions.Direction: Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
Cook sausage and crumble sausage in a pan oven medium heat. Set aside (do not drain excess grease).
Working in batches, puree the apples, onions, and celery in a food processor. Keep any liquid.
Add the cooked sausage, apples, onions, celery, and spices in a large bowl until combined.
Fold in croutons until evenly mixed (you may find it easier to mix with your hands).

(Skip this step if using to stuff a turkey). Starting with 1/2 c, pour chicken broth over the top of the stuffing and toss the croutons. The goal is to add a little bit of broth at a time until the croutons are moist, NOT soggy.
Place the stuffing in a large baking dish (you may need two) and cover with aluminum foil.
Bake for 35 minutes. Uncover and bake for an additional 20 minutes.
Serving with gravy and enjoy!

ingredients.Name: fresh thyme plus extra for garnish

directions.Direction: Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
Add creamed corn, corn, sour cream, butter, and thyme to a medium size bowl. Mix until combined.
Add in the Jiffy mix and stir until combined.
Pour into a greased 8x8 baking dish.
Bake for 50-60 minutes or until golden brown and cooked through.
Garnish with extra butter, honey, red pepper flakes, and fresh thyme.
